I don't think the azure registry has made the auth file different, I think Docker upstream may have.  I'm running Docker
```
# docker version
Client:
 Version:           18.09.8
 API version:       1.39
 Go version:        go1.13beta1
 Git commit:        0dd43dd
 Built:             Fri Jul 26 03:04:01 2019
 OS/Arch:           linux/amd64
 Experimental:      false
```
and my Podman auth file which used to look like Docker's earlier versions looks like:
```
# cat /run/user/0/containers/auth.json
{
	"auths": {
		"docker.io": {
			"auth": "dG....="
		}
	}
```
But as @QiWang19 pointed out, the Docker authfile now looks like:
```
# cat ~/.docker/config.json
{
	"auths": {
		"": {
			"auth": "dG....="
		}
	},
	"HttpHeaders": {
		"User-Agent": "Docker-Client/18.09.8 (linux)"
	}
}
```

So rather than the repo host, `docker.io`, it appears docker has blanked that out.  If I `docker login quay.io`, it adds that in ala:

```
# cat ~/.docker/config.json
{
	"auths": {
		"": {
			"auth": "dG....="
		},
		"quay.io": {
			"auth": "dG....="
		}
	},
	"HttpHeaders": {
		"User-Agent": "Docker-Client/18.09.8 (linux)"
	}
}
```

If that field is missing in the auth, we might be able to fill it in with 'docker.io', but that's kind of hacky.  @mtrmac any thoughts?
